diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can affect multiple systems in the body, potentially leading to acute pericarditis, pleural effusion, nephritis, delirium, and less commonly, psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Diseases
diagnoses.rationale: Various infections, such as viral or bacterial, can cause acute pericarditis, pleural effusion, delirium, and in rare cases, psychosis. Certain infections can also lead to nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Endocarditis could lead to acute pericarditis. The systemic effects of the infection can result in pleural effusion, delirium, and in rare instances, psychosis. Kidney involvement could result in nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease can cause a wide array of symptoms similar to other autoimmune disorders including acute pericarditis, pleural effusion, and nephritis. Neurological manifestations can include psychosis and delirium.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced Causes
diagnoses.rationale: Certain drugs can induce nephritis, psychosis, and delirium. Drug-induced lupus can cause acute pericarditis and pleural effusion.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.rationale: Though less common in developed countries, rheumatic fever can result in acute pericarditis and nephritis. It can also present with syndromes that resemble psychosis and can lead to pleural effusion.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: Sarcoidosis can involve the heart, leading to acute pericarditis, lungs causing pleural effusion, kidneys resulting in nephritis, and rarely, the central nervous system causing psychosis or delirium.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: Specific types of vasculitis can affect the kidneys (nephritis), heart (pericarditis), and lungs (pleural effusion). CNS involvement can lead to symptoms like delirium and psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Uremia
diagnoses.rationale: Uremia, resulting from kidney failure, can cause pleural effusion and acute pericarditis. It can also lead to neurological symptoms such as delirium and psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.rationale: Tuberculosis can cause pleural effusion and acute pericarditis. TB affecting the kidneys can lead to nephritis. In systemic cases, it can cause delirium or psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can lead to a wide range of complications including pericarditis, seizures due to neurological involvement, atrophic scarring as part of skin manifestations, and thrombocytopenia.

diagnoses.name: Mixed connective tissue disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD presents features of various autoimmune diseases including SLE, creating a spectrum of symptoms such as pericardial effusion, neurologic disorders, skin changes, and thrombocytopenia.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: Though primarily affecting joints, rheumatoid arthritis can cause pericarditis, have neurologic complications leading to seizures, induce cutaneous manifestations, and sometimes result in thrombocytopenia.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma (Systemic sclerosis)
diagnoses.rationale: Scleroderma can cause atrophic scarring due to skin involvement, pericardial effusion as a part of visceral manifestation, and has been associated with thrombocytopenia.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: This disease primarily increases the risk of blood clots but can cause a wide array of complications including thrombocytopenia. Its vascular effects might indirectly be involved with seizures, pericardial effusion, and acute pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Infectious pericarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Infections, including viral or bacterial, can lead to acute pericarditis and pericardial effusion. Depending on the causative agent, it might also predispose to seizures, thrombocytopenia, and result in various skin manifestations including atrophic scarring.

diagnoses.name: Cancer with pericardial involvement
diagnoses.rationale: Certain cancers can metastasize to the pericardium causing pericardial effusion or acute pericarditis. Paraneoplastic syndromes might cause thrombocytopenia and seizures, with treatments potentially leading to atrophic scarring.

diagnoses.name: Viral infections (e.g., HIV, Hepatitis)
diagnoses.rationale: Some viral infections can lead to a broad spectrum of symptoms including pericardial effusion, seizures (due to central nervous system involvement), atrophic scarring (skin lesions or as a treatment effect), and thrombocytopenia.

diagnoses.name: Uremia
diagnoses.rationale: Uremia, often a result of kidney failure, can cause pericarditis, affect platelet function leading to thrombocytopenia, and might be associated with neurologic complications such as seizures.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced lupus
diagnoses.rationale: Certain medications can induce a lupus-like syndrome featuring pericarditis, potential skin manifestations like atrophic scarring, thrombocytopenia, and less commonly seizures.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition characterized by intense headaches often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound. Scintillation (visual disturbances) and numbness can also be aura symptoms preceding the headache.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death. Symptoms can include headache, numbness or weakness in the face, arm, or leg, especially on one side of the body, along with possible trouble speaking, walking, or seeing.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it’s characterized by temporary blockage of blood flow to the brain, causing short-lived symptoms similar to a stroke, such as numbness and difficulties with vision.

diagnoses.name: Brain Aneurysm
diagnoses.description: A bulge or ballooning in a blood vessel in the brain. It can leak or rupture, causing bleeding into the brain (hemorrhagic stroke). Symptoms might include a sudden, severe headache, nausea and vomiting, and numbness.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In some cases, migraine-like symptoms such as headaches, nausea, and sensitivity to light/sound may occur.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain that can be cancerous or noncancerous. Depending on the tumor's location, it can cause headaches, nausea, seizures, vision problems, numbness, or other neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). MS blocks messages between the brain and the body, causing symptoms like fatigue, walking difficulties, numbness, muscle stiffness or spasms, and cognitive changes.

diagnoses.name: Hypertensive Crisis
diagnoses.description: A severe increase in blood pressure that can lead to a stroke. Symptoms may include a severe headache, nausea or vomiting, and neurological symptoms such as confusion, changes in vision, or numbness.

diagnoses.name: Carbon Monoxide Poisoning
diagnoses.description: Exposure to carbon monoxide gas can be fatal. Early symptoms mimic the flu (without fever) and can include headache, nausea, vomiting, and dizziness. Over time, symptoms may escalate to confusion, weakness, and numbness.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system (neurological) disorder where brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Specific types of seizures may also cause headache and sensory disturbances.
